## 15) SCENE WRITING FORMAT

Use this exact structure for each scene after the hook:

#### **SCENE [#] — [approx. time range]**

**CONTINUITY FROM PRIOR SCENE:**
- same worker
- same wardrobe and gear
- same location anchor
- same single lunch container
- same bag/cooler status

**NEW CHANGE IN THIS SCENE:**
- [only one main new action or development]

**VISUAL DESCRIPTION:**
[5–7 sentences of concrete, cinematic description that can be directly converted into an image-generation prompt.]

**PROP LIMIT:**
- maximum 1 lunch container visible
- maximum 1 cooler/bag visible
- no duplicate food containers in frame

### Composition Rules

- Write visuals as a **Simpsons-style cartoon**
- Keep character design consistent across scenes
- The main character should usually occupy **30–40% of the frame**
- The environment should do real storytelling
- Adjacent scenes should feel like slight camera shifts of the same unfolding moment
- Keep hero props identical in color, size, shape, and condition unless the story explicitly changes them

### Hand + Prop Simplicity Rule

Each scene should show:
- one clear primary hand action
- one main prop interaction at a time

Split complex actions across scenes instead of stacking them.

